{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_1lichtenstein_ver02/data/sn83045462/00280601676/1938010401/0479.xml":{"full_text":"SLAP HELD KELT\nPrediction Certain Foreign\nGovernments Will Not Last\nRegarded Precedent.\nBy DEWITT MACKENZIE.\nAssociated Press Foretrn Affairs Writer.\nNEW YORK, Jan. 4\u2014 President\nRoosevelt's reference to non-dem\nocratic nations which have violated\ntreaties, and his striking prediction\nthat representative form of govern\nment will return to, or be established\nin, those countries now lacking it,\ncomes at a moment when the total\nitarian \u201cisms\u201d are making a heavy\nassault on democracy.\nIndeed, even as Mr. Roosevelt was\ngiving his message to Congress,\nFascist Italy was commemorating the\nthirteenth birthday of the country as\na totalitarian state with nation-wide\ndemonstrations of satisfaction at \u201cdis\npersion of so-called great democracies\nlodged in the fortress at Geneva, which\nis crumbling before a formidabe array\n\u00a9f young peoples, the bearers of a\nnew civilization.\"\nDistinct Points.\nThe President didn\u2019t name any na\ntion, but his language was so very\nelear that he didn\u2019t have to in order\nto pin the thing down where he\nwanted it. He made two distinct\npoints:\n1. \u201cDisregard for treaty obligations\nseems to have followed the surface\ntrend away from the democratic rep\nresentative form of government. It\nwould seem, therefore, that world\npeace through international agree\nments, is most safe in the hands\nof democratic representative govern\nments\u2014or, in other words, peace is\nmost greatly jeopardized in and by\nthose nations where democracy has\nbeen discarded or has never devel\noped.\n3. \u201cI have used the words \u2019surface\ntrend,\u2019 for I still believe that civilized\nman increasingly insists and in the\nlong run will insist on genuine par\nticipation in his own government. Our\npeople believe that over the years de\nmocracies or the world will survive,\nand demooracv will be restored or es\ntablished in those nations which to\nday know it not. In that faith lies\nthe future peace of mankind.\u201d\nPrediction Held Unprecedented.\nThe moderation of the President's\nlanguage almost conceals the momen- i\ntous fact that he is making a predic- 1\ntion almost unprecedented for a chief\nof state\u2014the forecast that the govern\nI ments of certain foreign nations can\nnot last.\nThe words \"those nations where de\nmocracy has been discarded or has\nnever developed\u201d speak for themselves.\nThe leading nations which have dis\ncarded democracy are Italy and Ger\nmany, although many smaller countries\nhave followed suit. Democracy \"has i\nnever developed\" in Japan, which also\nIs under absolutism. It is not quite so\neasy to place Russia, which theoretic\nally is headed for rule by the prole\ntariat but actually is under a dictator\nchip.\nHere are some of the things which\nhave happened to democracy under\nthe \u201cisms\u201d:\nThe rights of the individual\u2014rich or\npoor\u2014have been wholly subordinated\nto the good of the state, which means\nthe will of the dictator.\nThe franchise virtually has disap-\npeered, excepting the right to vote for\nhand-picked candidates, or to indorse\nactions of a dictator.\nAll political parties are abolished ex\ncepting the one\u2014Fascist, Nazi or Com\nmunist.\nIn Germany and Russia religious\nfreedom has been suppressed. In Ger\nmany many Protestant and Catholic\nclergymen have been imprisoned, and\nthere is a large movement to give\nAdolf Hitler a religious significance.\nIn Russia there is no God at all for\nthe average Communist.\nOpposition Met by Force.\nOpposition is stifled by force. In\nRussia there is a constant \u201cblood\npurge,\" and Hitler had his terrible\nhouse-cleaning, when scores were\nkilled.\nCitizens are afraid to mention politi\ncal matters in public, for government\nspies lurk everywhere.\nThe government tells you w hat books\nand periodicals you may read, what\nmusic you may hear and what plays\nmay be seen.\nIn some countries there is class or\nrace persecution. In Germany it is\ndirected against the Jews. In Russia\nthe rich farmers get it.\nBig families are urged, and the pub\nlic schools grind into the children,\neven little ones, militarism and the\nprinciples of the particular \u201cism\" in\nvolved.\nregards the violation of treaties,\nthese charges have been made in\nGeneva:\nThat Japan by her conquests in\nChina has violated the Nine-Power\nTreaty, promising to respect the in\ntegrity of China, and the Kellogg\nBriand Peace Pact, japan also was\naccused of violating the League of\nNations covenant when she invaded\nManchuria.\nThat Germany threw overboard\nsaiUMUy th* entlr* Treaty of Ver*\nR\u2122at Ial.y violated the Kellogg\nBriand pact and the covenant of the\nleague in waging war on Ethiopia.\nHan Throws Sea Lion.\n/tFN,\u00a3?LI1 \u00aeEACH, Oreg., Jan. 3\nBay Aquarium had\nne^ exhibit today and Mike\nSchroeder of Oienenden Beach had\nK&2 title.ClRlm sea K\nMike clinched with the off-shore\nmeanie when the lion ran aground\nchasing a perch. Mike\u2019s water spaniel,\nCoony, kept the record clear by dash\ning into the surf and throwing the\nfish for a loss, too.\nRoosevelt\u2019s Speech\nSpares Republican\nBlow Torch Blast\nBy th* Associated Press.\nROMEO, Mich., Jan. 4.\u2014Dan\nrrost, a lifelong Republican,\nreadily admitted today he was in\ndebted to President Roosevelt.\nWhile thawing frosen water\n2pes in the attic with a blow\nrch, Mr. Frost was interrupted\nJ>7 his wife who called him down\nstairs to hear the President\u2019s mes\nsage on the radio.\nJ As Mr. Frost was taking his seat\nat the radio, the blow torch, which\n)ie had left in the attic, blew\n\u2022part, demolishing part of the\nroof.\nI \"I guess I got a new deal,\u201d\nsaid.\nk~-'A\nTanker Crashes Shore in Fog\nOff course in a heavy fog, the Los Angeles-bound tanker pictured as it ran ashore in a ship\nyard at Seattle and pushed her prow 200 feet up a marine railway.\u2014Copyright, A. P. Wirephoto.\nPapers\u2019 Views of Message\nPresident\u2019s Speech to Congress Draws Praise and\nCriticism From Nation\u2019s Editors.\nFollowing are extracts from editorial\ncomment of newspapers throughout\nthe United States on President Roose\nvelt\u2019s address, as gathered by the As\nsociated Press:\nNew York Daily News (Independent)\n\u2014In holding his majority popular sup\nport and reaching out for more of it.\nPresident Roosevelt seems to be doing\npretty well. But the way he\nangles for these various elements is\nnot, as charged, by preaching unsound\neconomics. The President's basic eco\nnomic beliefs are sound, we are con\nvinced.\nNew York Times (Independent Dem\nocratic)\u2014The message is the\nmessage for which many middle-of\nthe-road men have been waiting. In\nit, to be sure, there are certain rec\nommendations whose wisdom may be\nquestioned, but, by and large,\nthe message is reasonable in its ob\njectives, praiseworthy in its tone and\nfair in its treatment of those who dis\nagree with specific points in the ad\nministration\u2019s program.\nNew York Heral Tribune (Independ\nent Republican)\u2014The calm tone of\nthe President\u2019s message is a welcome\nrelief after the Jackson diatribes and\nthe Ickes hysterics. The sub\nstance of the document is, unfortu\nnately. another matter. The President\nis hardly at his best in discussing\nbasic economic problems. The\ntopic foremost is every one\u2019s mind, the\nbusiness slump, is but mentioned.\nMiami (Fla.) Herald (Independent\nDemocratic)\u2014The real business man,\nconstructively building up his own\nline and dealing fairly with his fellow\nmen, need have no fear of what the\nGovernment may do, seems to be the\nidea the President sought to empha\nsize.\nThe Oregonian (Independent Repub\nlican), Portland. Oreg.\u2014The Presi\ndent's message is remarkable chiefly\nfor comparative mildness.\nMr. Roosevelt still labors under the\nerror of thinking that his re-election\nin 1936 constituted a blanket approval\nof any and all legislative meas\nures he might see fit to dictate to\nCongress.\nMr. Roosevelt for the first time,\nthough very guardedly, reminds la\nbor that it, too, has responsibilities.\nBut he gives no notice to labor, as he\ndoes to business, that he will move\nto see that those responsibili\nties are assumed.\nBoston Herald (Republican)\u2014The\naddress was a comforting contrast\nIn tone and content to the recent\nspeeches of Secretary Ickes and As\nsistant Attorney General Jackson.\nWhen the President declared that\ni government can furnish specific\nacts of spoliation but cannot \"con\nscript co-operation\u201d he expressed a\ntruth which his two associates chose\nto ignore. A New Deal policy founded\nin that old, sound principle and pur\nsued consistently would do more than\nin additional billion of Federal hand\nouts. The address as a whole de\nserves commendation.\nBoston Globe (independent) \u2014In\nthe address is little echo of the re\ntent utterances of Secretary Ickes and\nAssistant Attorney General Jackson,\n:he President being milder than many\nlad anticipated and emphasizing his\n3 is position to co-operate with those\noy whom a spirit of helpfulness is\nshown.\nBaltimore Sun (independent Dem\n>crat)\u2014The mental somersaulting\nfoes on in this latest address of the\nPresident. In one place he is indi\nrectly lauding the N. R. a. in his\nreferences to the minimum-wage and\nmaximum-hour provisions of the codes\n\u2014provisions that were directly related\nto the monopolistic price and produc\ntion controls\u2014and in another place\nIn this speech he is criticizing mo\nnopoly and promising recommenda\ntions for its cure. The sum\nmary of the Nation\u2019s position in in\nternational affairs was sound\nand sensible, and it did not meet\nitself coming back.\nPittsburgh Post-Gaiette (Repub\nlican)\u2014* The President did not\nsay what we believe the majority of\nthe American people wanted to hear.\nThey wanted him to go as far\nas possible to encourage Industry.\nThe recession is the most\nvital problem. Why should\nthere be any delay in considering its\ncure? Why should a conference of\nGovernment, industry and labor of\nthis subject be postponed?\nAll in all. Mr. Roosevelt\u2019s message\nwas disappointing. Our hope now lies\nin Congress. An independent Con\ngress can and should do the things\nneeded to halt the present de\ni cline.\nLos Angeles Times (Republican)\nIn his advocacy of wages-and-hours\nlegislation the President evidenced an\napparently hopeless muddle of thought\nand a dismaying ignorance of the true\nnature of w-ealth. He made it plain\nthat, he considers the money earnings\nof wage-earners and their real sav\nings to be equivalent, with no thought\nof what the money will buy; and he\nalso made it plain that he lacks un\nderstanding of the real nub of the\nproblem of raising wages. Increased\nwages can come only from increased\nproduction; the President seems to\nthink they can be had by demanding\nthem.\nRichmond (V\u00bb.) Tima*-Dispatch\n(Independent-Democratic) \u2014President\nRoosevelt s message to Congress was\nrestrained, dignified, and, on the\nwhole, reasonable. In refreshing con\ntrast to the incendiary broadside de\nlivered last week by Secretary Ickes,\nit did not seek to place sole blame\nfor the recession an any one group\nof Americar. citizens. It was notably\nfree from threats and bombast, and,\nwhile it exhibited firmness and cour\nage, there was nothing in it to cause\ndismay to honest business.\nThe Newark (N. J.) Ledger (Inde\npendent)\u2014If yesterday\u2019s message, in\nits very mildness, was a sharp con\ntrast to other Roosevelt pronounce\nments, it was because the message was\ndelivered against a greatly changed\nbackground. In this background three\nnew elements loomed large\u20141, the\nbusiness recession; 2. the revolt of\nCongress in the special session, and 3,\nthe reaction of displeasure among the\npubic caused by the incendiary, class\nconscious speeches of two New Deal\nspokesmen. Assistant Attorney Gen\neral Jackson and Secretary of the\nInterior Ickes.\nWorcester (Mass.) Post (Independ\nent)\u2014Those who looked for bomb\nshells in the President\u2019s message to\nCongress today were disappointed.\nWhat he offered was a thoughtful and\nintelligent analysis of the state of the\nNation and a statement of the admin\nistration\u2019s purpose. He was wise in\nmaking this message conciliatory.\nNothing could go further to break the\ndeadlock of distrust, which now grips\nthe Government and Nation, than this\ncandid statement of the President's\noutlook. We hope that it will be re\nceived in the spirit in which it was\ngiven.\nRochester (N. Y.) Democrat and\nChronicle (Independent)\u2014The con\nciliatory tone of the message is salu\ntary, following the extreme attacks\nrecently made by Secretary Ickes and\nAssistant Attorney General Robert\nJackson. If the n^w session will make\ndefinite moves toward the modifica\ntions in Government tax policies the\nPresident admits are necessary, busi\nness may be expected to meet the\nGovernment half way in a policy of\nco-operation. There is every reason\nwhy it should do so.\nDeficit\n'Continued From First Page.)\nbut the deficit would be smaller than\nthis year's.\nSecretary Morgenthau, comment\ning on the President's announcement,\nsaid that business conditions had\nchanged the situation completely sine*\nhe and Mr. Roosevelt had expressed\nhope in the fall of achieving a bal\nance.\n\"If business should pick up, we\ncould still balance the budget,\" he\nsaid.\nThe President expects to send his\n1938-9 budget to Congress tomorrow,\nbut probably will tell the lawmakers\nthat next year\u2019s relief needs cannot\nbe estimated for a few more months.\nThe budget figures on naval con\nstruction also will be tentative.\nThe continuance of an unbalanced\nbudget, laid chiefly to relief needs aris\ning from the business recession, point\ned up the current congressional issue\nof whether to trim expenses gr to\nspend heavily to create work for the\nunemployed.\nPresident Roosevelt has proposed\ncurtailing Federal aid for highways,\nreducing the enrollment of the Civilian\nConservation Corps, and generally\ntightening departmental expenses.\nThe new session of Congress was\ncertain to hear strenuous objections\nto the highway and C. C. C. reduc\ntions. together with new demands for\nexpansion of the W. P. A.\nOfficial figures showing the unem\nployed between 7.822,912 and 10.870.\n000 were relied on by proponents of\nGovernment spending as giving sup\nport to their contention that Govern\nment still must \"take up the slack\" in\nproviding work.\nRepresentative \u201eDles, Democrat, of i\nTexas, leader of a House \"economy\"\ngroup, said the President\u2019s message\nconvinced him \"there is not much use\nof our going ahead\" with plans to\nbalance the budget.\nMr. Dies said, however, his bloc\nmight still try to frame some recom\nmendations \"behind which the Presi\ndent can rally the .House to effect\neconomies.\"\nThe officials who predicted that Mr.\nRoosevelt's revised estimates for this\nfiscal year would set the deficit at\n$1,230,000,000, said his previous esti\nmate of $895,245,000 deficit was made\nOctober 19, before the extent of the\nbusiness recession could be guaged.\nIn the year ended June 30, 1934,\nthe deficit was $3,965,992,000. Pre\nvious deficits in the Roosevelt admini\nstration were: 1934-35, $3,082,129,000;\n1935-36, $4,810,894,000, and 1936-37,\n$2,811,318,000.\nExpenditures reached a peak of\n$8,781,388,000 in the 1935-36 year, and\nthe Presidents October estimate\nplaced this year's spending at $7,545,\n655,000. He told Congress yesterday\nexpenditures cannot be cut much be\nlow $7,000,000,000.\n\nPass First-Aid Test.\nMore than 10,000 employes of a\nBritish railway have passed examina\ntions In first aid.\n1937 AND 1938\nFLOOR SAMPLES\n$59.95 Granow_$30\n$79.95 Philco_$40\n$89.95 RCA-Victor $45\n$99.95 Granow_$50\n$99.95 RCA-Victor $50\n$104.50 Philco_$53\n$149.50 Granow_$75\n$164.50 Philco_$85\nMany Other*\u2014Easy Term*\u2014New Guarantee\nQRDAN\nB\u00bb 0 Street IJfl GmfflNW\nROOSEVELT WORDS\nSCORED BY GAYDA\nItalian Fascist Authority\nSees Speech Furthering\nWorld Hostility.\nBl ths Associated Press.\nROME, Jan. 4.\u2014Virginlo Oayda, au\nthoritative Fascist editor, declared to\nday that President Roosevelt\u2019s message\nto Congress had furthered creation of\na state of permanent International\nhostility.\nOayda, whose writings often reflect\nthe official Italian viewpoint, in an\neditorial In his Oiornale d'ltalla, said:\n\"President Roosevelt insists upon\ndividing the world into two parts, the\ndemocracies and the authoritative re\ngimes, and upon creating between one\nand the other a state of permanent\ndiffidence and hostility, contradicting\nthose principles of conciliation and\ncollaboration which he claimed for his\npolicy.\u2019\u2019\nOayda asserted the authoritarian^-e\ngimes had appealed vainly for a peace\nful solution of their problems, but\nthese appeals had been rejected by the\ndemocracies.\nt\nRoosevelt Speech Greeted.\nLONDON, Jan. 4 UP).\u2014Europe's great\ndemocracies and the League of Na\ntions last night expressed warm ap\nproval of President Roosevelt\u2019s message\nto Congress, especially his assertion\nthe world's peace was \u201cmost safe in\nthe hands of Democratic representative\ngovernments.\u201d\nIn France and Oreat Britain na\ntion-wide applause greeted his state\nment of the American people's belief\nthat democracy would \"be restored or\nestablished in those nations which\ntoday know it not,\u201d and his declara\ntion that \u201cin that faith lies the future\npeace of mankind.\u201d\nSources close to the British gov\nernment declared that Europe gener\nally\u2014Germany and Italy excepted\u2014\nwelcomed what they called a bold\ncondemnation of the policies of dic\ntatorial countries.\nleague circles at Geneva hailed the\nPresident's prophecy of a return of\ndemocracy to totalitarian states as a\nprediction of a similar return to in\nternational collaboration through the\nLeague.\nBritish quarters expressed disap\npointment that Roosevelt had failed\nto elaborate the extent of the leader\nship the United States was prepared\nto take in curbing international law\nlessness.\nDemocracies Challenged.\nBERLIN, Jan. 4 <\u00a3*).\u2014Commenting\non President Roosevelt's speech, a\nGerman foreign office spokesman to\nday said \"democracies have failed so\nfar to prove they alone can safeguard\npeace in the world or otherwise we\nwould not have war in the Par East.\u201d\nThe spokesman emphasized that\nthe speech still is being examined in\nBerlin and. because only the con\ndensed version is available, \"we do\nnot have the proper perspective on\nthe full speech.\u201d\nGermany has given \"sufficient evi\ndence of safeguarding peace.\" he\nsaid, adding \"democracy and dictator\nship are two concepts which never\nwill march together.\u201d\nWarning to Dictators Seen.\nBy PERTINAX.\nPARIS, Jan. 4 (N.AN.A.).\u2014Presi\ndent Roosevelt's message to Congress\nis interpreted here as a timely warn\ning to the totalitarian states.\nIt is remarked that the President\nwent much further than on October 5\nwhen he delivered his Chicago speech.\nThen he referred to the economic re\npression of aggressors, but at the same\ntime boasted that America would never\nwage war, and because of that contra\ndiction the whole address was deprived\nof practical meaning.\nNow he proclaims that a peaceful\nnation must be strong enough to. im\npose peaceful settlement of interna\ntional conflicts. It is inferred from\nthat phrase by most political observ\ners that the President leads his peo\nple toward adoption of a huge pro\ngram of armaments, which, by the\nway, is believed likely to prove a stimu\nlus to depressed American economy\nand may reawaken the heavy indus\ntries, which, as a result of investors\u2019\nabstention, never had its share of the\n1935-37 recovery. But it is above all\nas a repudiation of isolationism, with\nwhich Berlin, Rome and Tokio will\nhave to reckon, that the presidential\nmessage is welcomed.\n(Copyrlcht. 1938. by the North American\nNewspaper Alliance, Inc.)\nPENNSYLVANIA PRESSES\n44-HOUR-LAW FIGHT\nBy the Associated Frets.\nHARRISBURG. Pa., Jan. 4.\u2014Ralph\nM. Bashore, state secretary of labor\nand Industry, made good his threat to\nday to \"crack down\u201d on violators of\nthe new 44-hour law, while Attorney\nGeneral Charles J. Margiottl pressed\nfor a test of the act In the Supreme\nCourt.\nBashore announced that he had\nreceived hundreds of \u2018\u2022tips\" of vio\nlations of the besieged act and that\nhis department was checking up on\nthese with a view to prosecution.\nIn Philadelphia, where the Supreme\nCourt was In session, the attorney\ngeneral said that he would confer this\nweek with counsel for 187 industrial\nconcern* which challenged the con\nstitutionality of the law.\nCombating tbo Pain of\nArthritis\nThouaanda aufferlni from arthritis palna\nera* wiTt2rh* rtirJ2.tMOfUnUln ,v*Ue\u00bb \u00bb\u00abm!\na*r\u00abct from famous Hot\n\u00a5Jld\u2018* Alkaline Daep?;\n\u00ae*tisfyina. Indorsed by physicians for\norer 30 rear. Phon. Met. 1082 f\u201c*e&r.\nZwt ,^L1 Vall,y Mineral Water\nAT JORDAN'S\nYou Con Choose From the\nLargest Selection of\nSpinette Pianos\nin the city nine fine makes'\nLENOX SPINETTE\nA charming little plain style\nspinette designed for tiny\napartments at the lowest\nprice we\u2019ve ever seen 1JQ\non a real piano_\nCOLONIAL SPINETTE\nA new model made by Hunt\nington. Charmingly designed\nand nicely finished. It\u2019s a\npiano that any fam- J1 QC\nily would be proud of\nWINTER LOWBOY\nA Colonial lowboy model\nthat's (me of our best sellers,\nand, we believe, the biggest\npiano value on the market\ntoday. Available in\nmahogany and wal- <229\nnut\nVERY EASY TERMS\